Packages.Name: colorutil
Packages.Synopsis: Utilities for parsing and manipulating colors.

Functions.Name: BenchmarkKelvinToColor
Functions.Comment:
This benchmark is here both to validate the speed, but also to ensure none of this
wild floating point math accumulates any noticable errors.

Functions.Name: Equals
Functions.Comment: Return whether two colors are equivalent in the 24-bit RGB (RGB255) color space.

Functions.Name: HslToRgb
Functions.Comment:
Given HSL values (where hue is given in degrees (out of 360°), saturation
and lightness are [0, 1]), return the corresponding RGB values (where each value
is [0, 255]).
Functions.Signature: HslToRgb(hue float64, saturation float64, lightness float64) (uint8, uint8, uint8)

Functions.Name: HsvToRgb
Functions.Comment:
Given HSL values (where hue is given in degrees (out of 360°), saturation
and value are [0, 1]), return the corresponding RGB values (where each value
is [0, 255]).
Functions.Signature: HsvToRgb(hue float64, saturation float64, value float64) (uint8, uint8, uint8)

Functions.Name: KelvinToColor
Functions.Comment:
Takes a color temperature in degrees Kelvin and returns a valid Color for that temperature.
This function works best between 1000K and 40000K.

Functions.Name: RgbToHsl
Functions.Comment:
Given RGB values (where each value is [0, 255]), return the hue (in degrees), saturation,
and lightness (where each is [0, 1]).
Functions.Signature: RgbToHsl(r float64, g float64, b float64) (float64, float64, float64)

Methods.Name: Equals
Methods.Comment: Return whether the given color is equal to this one in the 24-bit RGB (RGB255) color space

Methods.Name: HSI
Methods.Comment: Return the current color as hue (out of 360°), saturation [0, 1], and intensity [0, 1].

Methods.Name: HSL
Methods.Comment: Return the current color as hue (out of 360°), saturation [0, 1], and lightness [0, 1].

Methods.Name: HSV
Methods.Comment: Return the current color as hue (out of 360°), saturation [0, 1], and value [0, 1].

Methods.Name: NativeRGBA
Methods.Comment: Return the color as a color.RGBA struct.

Methods.Name: RGBA
Methods.Comment: Return the current color as a 32-bit uint quad, implementing the color.Color interface.

Methods.Name: RGBA255
Methods.Comment: Return the current color as 4x 8-bit RGB values, each [0, 255].

Methods.Name: MustParse
Methods.Comment: Parse the given value into a Color or panic.

Methods.Name: Parse
Methods.Comment: Parse the given value into a Color or return an error.

Methods.Name: Darken
Methods.Comment:
Darken the given color by a certain percent.  Consistent with the results of the
Sass darken() function.

Methods.Name: Lighten
Methods.Comment:
Lighten the given color by a certain percent.  Consistent with the results of the
Sass lighten() function.

Methods.Name: Saturate
Methods.Comment:
Saturate the given color by a certain percent.  Consistent with the results of the
Sass saturate() function.

Methods.Name: Desaturate
Methods.Comment:
Desaturate the given color by a certain percent.  Consistent with the results of the
Sass desaturate() function.

Methods.Name: AdjustHue
Methods.Comment: Adjust the hue of the given color by the specified number of degrees.

Methods.Name: MixN
Methods.Comment:
Mix two colors, producing a third.  The weight value specifies how much of the first color
should be included.  Consistent with the results of the Sass mix() function.
Methods.Signature: MixN(first interface{}, second interface{}, weight float64) (Color, error)

Methods.Name: Mix
Methods.Comment: Mix two colors in equal parts, producing a third.

Functions.Name: Convert
Functions.Signature: Convert(in interface{}, from interface{}, to interface{}) (float64, error)

Functions.Name: ExactConvert
Functions.Signature: ExactConvert(in interface{}, from interface{}, to interface{}) (float64, error)

Functions.Name: MustConvert
Functions.Signature: MustConvert(in interface{}, from interface{}, to interface{}) float64

Functions.Name: MustExactConvert
Functions.Signature: MustExactConvert(in interface{}, from interface{}, to interface{}) float64

Packages.Name: executil
Packages.Synopsis: Utilities that make executing commands on the local system a little bit easier.

Functions.Name: FindShell
Functions.Comment:
Uses environment variables and other configurations to attempt to locate the
path to the user's shell.

Functions.Name: IsRoot
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the current user is root or not.

Functions.Name: Join
Functions.Comment: Take an *exec.Cmd or []string and return a shell-executable command line string.

Functions.Name: MustShellOut
Functions.Comment: A panicky version of ShellOut.

Functions.Name: MustSplit
Functions.Comment: Same as Split, but panics if there is an error.

Functions.Name: PromptPassword
Functions.Comment: Generic password prompt that takes the input file descriptor and verify flag as options.
Functions.Signature: PromptPassword(writer io.Writer, fd int, verify bool) (string, bool)

Functions.Name: ReadAndVerifyPassword
Functions.Comment:
Read a password from standard input, disabling echo and prompting twice.  The
second return argument is falseif the two passwords do not match.

Functions.Name: ReadPassword
Functions.Comment: Read a password from standard input, disabling echo.

Functions.Name: RootOr
Functions.Comment: Returns the first argument if the current user is root, and the second if not.

Functions.Name: RootOrString
Functions.Comment: The same as RootOr, but returns a string.

Functions.Name: ShellOut
Functions.Comment:
Run a command and return the standard output.  If the first argument contains
a command and its arguments, it will be executed in the user's shell using FindShell.
Otherwise, the first argument will be treated as a command and the remaining arguments
will be passed in parameterized.

Functions.Name: ShouldShellOut
Functions.Comment: Attempts to call ShellOut, but will return nil if there is an error.  Does not panic.

Functions.Name: ShouldSplit
Functions.Comment: Same as Split, but silently discards any errors, returning an empty slice in this case.

Functions.Name: Split
Functions.Comment: Splits the given string into words, honoring quoting and escaping conventions of common command line shells.

Functions.Name: TrapSignals
Functions.Comment:
Registers a list of OS signals to intercept and provides an opportunity to run
a function before the program exits.

Functions.Name: Which
Functions.Comment:
Locates the first path containing the given command. The directories listed
in the environment variable "PATH" will be checked, in order.  If additional
directories are specified in the path variadic argument, they will be checked
first.  If the command is not in any path, an empty string will be returned.

Functions.Name: WhichAll
Functions.Comment:
Locates the all paths containing the given command. The directories listed
in the environment variable "PATH" will be checked, in order.  If additional
directories are specified in the path variadic argument, they will be checked
first.  If the command is not in any path, an empty slice will be returned.

Cmd.Name: Cmd

Methods.Name: Kill
Methods.Comment: Kill the running command.

Methods.Name: Status
Methods.Comment: Return the current status of the process.

Methods.Name: WaitStatus
Methods.Comment:
Wait for the process to complete, then return the last status.
Process must have been started using the Start() function.

Fields.Name: MonitorInterval
Fields.Comment: An interval of time on which the command should be actively checked for run and exit status.

Fields.Name: Timeout
Fields.Comment: How long the command may run for before being killed.

Fields.Name: InheritEnv
Fields.Comment: Whether the command invocation should inherit the environment variables of the calling process.

Fields.Name: OnStart
Fields.Comment: Called when immediately before the command is executed.

Fields.Name: OnMonitor
Fields.Comment: Called whenever the monitor check is performed.

Fields.Name: OnComplete
Fields.Comment: Called when the command exits, regardless of success or failure.

Fields.Name: OnSuccess
Fields.Comment: Called when the command exits with a non-error status (code 0)

Fields.Name: OnError
Fields.Comment: Called when the command exits with an error status (non-zero exit code, security, invocation, or resource error)

Fields.Name: OnStdout
Fields.Comment: Called when a line of standard output is written.

Fields.Name: OnStderr
Fields.Comment: Called when a line of standard error is written.

Fields.Name: StdoutSplitFunc
Fields.Comment: If specified, this function will determine how to tokenize the stdout stream and when to call OnStdout.  Defaults to bufio.ScanLines.

Fields.Name: StderrSplitFunc
Fields.Comment: If specified, this function will determine how to tokenize the stderr stream and when to call OnStderr.  Defaults to bufio.ScanLines.

Fields.Name: InheritParent
Fields.Comment: Specifies that the spawned process should inherit the same Process Group ID (PGID) as the parent.

Cmd.Comment:
A wrapper for exec.Cmd that provides helpful callbacks and monitoring details that are challenging
to implement.

Packages.Name: fileutil
Packages.Synopsis: Helpers for working with files and filesystems

Variables.Name: DirExists
Variables.Comment: Alias functions from pathutil as a convenience

Variables.Name: SkipToken
Variables.Comment:
By default, the underlying bufio.Scanner that tokenizes the input data
will discard the tokens that it's splitting on.  however, in most cases, we
don't actually want this.  however, if the thing we're removing IS this token,
then we will have removed the token, then immediately put it back in the stream.

Returning the SkipToken error will tell the ReadManipulator to not put this token
back into the stream, but otherwise not produce an actual error during read.

Functions.Name: Cat
Functions.Comment: Attempt to call ReadAllString, but will return an empty string if there is an error.  Does not panic.

Functions.Name: CompareReaders
Functions.Comment:
Compare the binary contents of two io.Reader instances.  The result will be 0 if a==b, -1 if a < b, and +1 if a > b.
An optional hash.Hash instance may be given, otherwise the default crypto/sha256 will be used.
Functions.Signature: CompareReaders(a io.Reader, b io.Reader, hasher ...hash.Hash) int

Functions.Name: CopyDir
Functions.Comment:
Recursively walk the entries of a given directory, calling CopyEntryFunc for each entry.
The io.Writer returned from the function will have that file's contents written to it.  If
the io.Writer is nil, the file will not be written anywhere but no error will be returned.
If CopyEntryFunc returns an error, the behavior will be consistent with filepath.WalkFunc

Functions.Name: CopyFile
Functions.Comment:
Copy a file from one place to another.  Source can be an io.Reader or string.  If source is a
string, the string will be passed to the Open() function as a URL.  Destination can be an
io.Writer or string.  If destination is a string, it will be treated as a local filesystem path
to write the data read from source to.

If either source or destination implements io.Closer, thee files will be closed before this
function returns.

Functions.Name: GetMimeType
Functions.Comment:
GetMimeType goes out of its way to really, really try to figure out the MIME type of a given
filename or io.Reader.  If the first argument satisfies the io.Seeker interface, the seeker
will Seek() back to the beginning.  If it satisfies the io.Closer interface, it will be closed.

Functions.Name: GetNthLine
Functions.Comment: Attempt to return the nth line (starting from 1) in the given file or reader.

Functions.Name: IsModifiedAfter
Functions.Comment: Return true if the given FileInfo sports a ModTime later than the current file.

Functions.Name: MustGetNthLine
Functions.Comment: A panicky version of GetNthLine.

Functions.Name: MustReadAllLines
Functions.Comment: A panicky version of ReadAllLines.

Functions.Name: MustWriteFile
Functions.Comment: Same as WriteFile, but will panic if the file cannot be written.

Functions.Name: MustWriteTempFile
Functions.Comment:
Same as MustWriteFile, but writes the given input to a temporary file, returning
the filename.  The function will panic if the file cannot be written.

Functions.Name: Open
Functions.Comment: Calls OpenWithOptions with no options set.

Functions.Name: OpenWithOptions
Functions.Comment:
A generic URL opener that supports various schemes and returns an io.Reader.
Supported URL schemes include: file://, http://, https://, ftp://, sftp://. If no scheme is
provided, the URL is interpreted as a local filesystem path.

Functions.Name: ReadAll
Functions.Comment:
Takes the given string filename, []byte, io.Reader, or io.ReadCloser and returns
the bytes therein.

Functions.Name: ReadAllLines
Functions.Comment: Read all lines of text from the given file and return them as a slice.

Functions.Name: ReadAllString
Functions.Comment: A string version of ReadAll.

Functions.Name: RegisterOpenHandler
Functions.Comment: Register a handler for a new or existing URL scheme, for use with Open() and OpenWithOptions()

Functions.Name: RegisterRetrieveScheme
Functions.Comment: Register a new Retrieve() function for the given URL scheme.

Functions.Name: RemoveBlankLines
Functions.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for removing lines that only contain whitespace.

Functions.Name: RemoveOpenHandler
Functions.Comment: Removes a registered URL scheme handler.

Functions.Name: Retrieve
Functions.Comment:
Perform a generic retrieval of data located at a specified resource given as a URL.
This function supports file://, http://, https://, ssh://, and sftp:// schemes, and can
be extended to support additional schemes using the RegisterRetrieveScheme package function.

If resourceUri is given as a *url.URL, the value of that URL will be copied.  Any other type
will be converted to a string (honoring types that implement fmt.Stringer), and the resulting
URL will be used.

Functions.Name: RetrieveViaFilesystem
Functions.Comment:
Retrieve a file via a filesystem.  If the context value `filesystem` implements
the http.FileSystem interface, it will be used to perform the retrieval in lieu
of the local filesystem.

Functions.Name: RetrieveViaHTTP
Functions.Comment:
Retrieve a file via HTTP or HTTPS.

Supported Context Values:

 insecure:
   (bool) specify that strict TLS validation should be optional.

 method:
   (string) the HTTP method to use, defaults to GET.

 metadata:
   (map[string]interface{}) a key-value set of HTTP request headers to include.

 safeResponseCodes:
   ([]int) a list of one or more HTTP status codes that are considered successful for this request.

Functions.Name: RetrieveViaSSH
Functions.Comment:
Retrieve a file via SFTP (SSH file transfer).  The given URL should resemble the
prototype: ssh://[user:password@]hostname[:22]/path/relative/to/homedir

This function will honor any authentication details from a running SSH agent,
as well as utilize the private key located in the path indicated by SshPrivateKey
or via the `privateKey` context value.

Supported Context Values:

username:
  (string) the username to login with. can be overriden by a username specified in the URL.

password:
  (string) the password to login with. can be overriden by a password specified in the URL.

passphrase:
  (string) context value specifies a plaintext passphrase used to unlock the local private keyfile.

insecure:
  (bool) whether to ignore remote hostkey checks.  Does not work if verifyHostFunc is set.

verifyHostFunc:
  (SshHostKeyCallbackFunc) context value, if it is convertible to the ssh.HostKeyCallback type, will
  be called to verify the remote SSH host key in a manner of the function's choosing.  The default
  behavior is to accept all remote hostkeys as valid.

Functions.Name: SameFile
Functions.Comment:
Returns whether two files represent the same file.  If a string is given for either file, os.Stat will be run on that
path.  If os.FileInfo is given for either file, it will be passed to os.SameFile directly.  If either file is an
io.Reader, the contents of both files will be read and hashed using CompareHasher.  If the hashes are identical, the
files are considered the same.  Any error encountered and this function will return false.

Functions.Name: SetExt
Functions.Comment:
Detects the file extension of the given path and replaces it with the given extension.  The optional
second argument allows you to explictly specify the extension (if known).
Functions.Signature: SetExt(path string, ext string, oldexts ...string) string

Functions.Name: ShouldGetNthLine
Functions.Comment: Attempts to call GetNthLine, but will return an empty string if there is an error.  Does not panic.

Functions.Name: ShouldReadAllLines
Functions.Comment: Attempts to call ReadAllLines, but will return an empty slice if there is an error.  Does not panic.

Functions.Name: SizeOf
Functions.Comment: Returns the size of the given filename, or zero if any error is encountered (or if the file is zero length).

Functions.Name: UnregisterRetrieveScheme
Functions.Comment: Unregister the given URL scheme from being handled by the Retrieve() function.

Functions.Name: WriteFile
Functions.Comment:
Write the contents of the given io.Reader, []byte, or string to the specified filename.
Filename paths containing tilde (~) will automatically expand to the current
user's home directory, and all intermediate parent directories will be automatically
created.  Will return the number of bytes written, or an error.

Functions.Name: WriteTempFile
Functions.Comment:
Same as WriteFile, but writes the given input to a temporary file, returning
the filename.

DirReader.Name: DirReader

Methods.Name: Close
Methods.Comment: close open files and reset the internal reader

Methods.Name: SetSkipFunc
Methods.Comment:
Set a function that will be called for each path encountered while reading.
If this function returns true, that path (and its descedants) will not be read.

DirReader.Comment:
A DirReader provides a streaming io.Reader interface to all files in a given
directory, with options for handling unreadable entries and recursion.

FileInfo.Name: FileInfo
FileInfo.Comment: An os.FileInfo-compatible wrapper that allows for individual values to be overridden.

Methods.Name: NewPostReadCloser
Methods.Comment:
Implements an io.ReadCloser that can be configured to perform cleanup options whenever the
Close() function is called.  If CloserFunc is non-nil, it will be given the upstream ReadCloser
as an argument and will be responsible for calling Close() on it.  If nil, upstream's Close()
function will be called directly on Close.

Methods.Name: ManipulateAll
Methods.Comment:
Performs multiple sequential manipulations on an intercepted line of text from
an io.Reader as its being read.

Methods.Name: ReplaceWith
Methods.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for replacing text in an io.Reader as its being read.
Methods.Signature: ReplaceWith(find string, replace string, occurrences int) ReadManipulatorFunc

Methods.Name: RemoveLinesContaining
Methods.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for removing lines that contain the given string.

Methods.Name: RemoveLinesWithPrefix
Methods.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for removing lines that have a given prefix.

Methods.Name: RemoveLinesWithSuffix
Methods.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for removing lines that have a given suffix.

Methods.Name: RemoveLinesSurroundedBy
Methods.Comment: A ReadManipulatorFunc for removing lines surrounded by a given prefix and suffix.
Methods.Signature: RemoveLinesSurroundedBy(prefix string, suffix string, trimSpace bool) ReadManipulatorFunc

Packages.Name: geoutil
Packages.Synopsis: Types and functions for working with Geospatial Data

Location.Name: Location

Methods.Name: HaversineDistance
Methods.Comment:
Return the distance (in meters) between this point and another.  This calulates the
great-circle distance (shortest distance two points on the surface of a sphere) between
this Location and another.  Since this (incorrectly) assumes the Earth to be a true
sphere, this is only reasonably accurate for short-ish distances (is only accurate to
within ~0.5%).

Location.Comment: Specifies a three-dimensional location within a coordinate reference system.

LocationError.Name: LocationError
LocationError.Comment: Describes the error margin (+/-) for each of the named values.

Packages.Name: httputil
Packages.Synopsis: Utilities for extracting and formatting data encountered in HTTP requests

Functions.Name: AddQ
Functions.Comment: Appends a query string from then given url.URL

Functions.Name: AddQString
Functions.Comment:
A version of AddQ that accepts a URL string and makes a best-effort to modify it.
Will return the modified URL or the original URL if an error occurred.
Functions.Signature: AddQString(u string, key string, value interface{}) string

Functions.Name: DecodeResponse
Functions.Comment:
Takes an http.Response and returns an io.Reader that will return the contents
of the Response Body decoded according to the values (if any) of the Content-Encoding
response header.

Functions.Name: DelQ
Functions.Comment: Deletes a query string from then given url.URL

Functions.Name: DelQString
Functions.Comment:
A version of DelQ that accepts a URL string and makes a best-effort to modify it.
Will return the modified URL or the original URL if an error occurred.

Functions.Name: EncodeBasicAuth
Functions.Comment: Encode the username and password into a value than can be used in the Authorization HTTP header.

Functions.Name: GetBody
Functions.Comment:
A simplified GET function using the package-level default client.  Will return the
response body as bytes.

Functions.Name: Is1xx
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the given status code is 100 <= s <= 199

Functions.Name: Is2xx
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the given status code is 200 <= s <= 299

Functions.Name: Is3xx
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the given status code is 300 <= s <= 399

Functions.Name: Is4xx
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the given status code is 400 <= s <= 499

Functions.Name: Is5xx
Functions.Comment: Returns whether the given status code is 500 <= s <= 599

Functions.Name: IsMediaType
Functions.Comment:
Returns whether the Content-Type of the given request matches any of the supplied options.
The mediaTypes arguments may be either complete media types (e.g.: "text/html", "application/javascript")
or major type classes (e.g.: "text/", "video/").  The trailing slash (/) indicates that any media type
that begins with that text will match.

Functions.Name: LoadCertPool
Functions.Comment: Loads certificates from the given file and returns a usable x509.CertPool

Functions.Name: MediaType
Functions.Comment: Returns the media type from the request's Content-Type.

Functions.Name: MultipartFormEncoder
Functions.Comment: Specifies that the given data should be encoded as a multipart/form-data request.

Functions.Name: NetrcCredentials
Functions.Comment:
Retreive the plaintext username and password from the netrc-formatted file in the
NetrcFile package variable.  The final return argument will be true if and only if
the .netrc file exists, is readable, and the username OR password matched to the given
domain is non-empty.

Functions.Name: ParseFormRequest
Functions.Comment: Parses the form values for a Request and unmarshals into the given value.

Functions.Name: ParseFormValues
Functions.Comment:
Parses a set of values received from an HTML form (usually the value of the
http.Request.Form property) and unmarshals into the given value.

Functions.Name: ParseJSON
Functions.Comment: Parses a given reader as a JSON document and unmarshals into the given value.

Functions.Name: ParseJSONRequest
Functions.Comment: Parses the Request as JSON and unmarshals into the given value.

Functions.Name: ParseRequest
Functions.Comment:
Autodetect the Content-Type of the given request and unmarshals into the
given value.

Functions.Name: Q
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a string.

Functions.Name: QBool
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a boolean value.

Functions.Name: QDuration
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a duration string.

Functions.Name: QFloat
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a float.

Functions.Name: QInt
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as an integer.

Functions.Name: QStrings
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a delimiter-separated string slice.
Functions.Signature: QStrings(req *http.Request, key string, delimiter string, fallbacks ...string) []string

Functions.Name: QTime
Functions.Comment: Parses the named query string from a request as a date/time value.

Functions.Name: RequestGetValue
Functions.Comment: Retrieve an arbitrary value from the context of a given request.

Functions.Name: RequestSetValue
Functions.Comment: attach an arbitrary value to the context of a given request.

Functions.Name: RespondJSON
Functions.Comment:
Marshal the given data as a JSON document and write the output to the given ResponseWriter. If
a status is given, that will be used as the HTTP response status.  If data is an error, and no
status is given, the status will be "500 Internal Server Error"; if data is nil, the status will
be "204 No Content".  The Content-Type of the response is "application/json".

Functions.Name: SetContentTypeParser
Functions.Comment: Sets a parser implementation for the given HTTP content type.

Functions.Name: SetQ
Functions.Comment: Sets a query string to the given value in the given url.URL

Functions.Name: SetQString
Functions.Comment:
A version of SetQ that accepts a URL string and makes a best-effort to modify it.
Will return the modified URL or the original URL if an error occurred.
Functions.Signature: SetQString(u string, key string, value interface{}) string

Functions.Name: SetRootCABundle
Functions.Comment: Configures the given http.Client to accept TLS certificates validated by the given PEM-encoded CA bundle file

Functions.Name: UrlPathJoin
Functions.Comment:
UrlPathJoin takes a string or *url.URL and joins the existing URL path component with the given path.
The new path may also contain query string values, which will be added to the base URL.  Existing keys will
be replaced with new ones, except for repeated keys (e.g.: ?x=1&x=2&x=3).  In this case, the new values will
be added to the existing ones.  The *url.URL returned from this function is a copy, and the original URL (if
one is provided) will not be modified in any way.

Functions.Name: WaitForHTTP
Functions.Comment:
Periodically performs a GET request against the given URL, waiting up to timeout
for a 200-series HTTP response code.
Functions.Signature: WaitForHTTP(url string, timeout time.Duration, c ...*http.Client) error

Methods.Name: AppendTrustedRootCA
Methods.Comment: Append one or more trusted certificates to the RootCA bundle that is consulted when performing HTTPS requests.

Methods.Name: ClearHeaders
Methods.Comment: Remove all implicit HTTP request headers.

Methods.Name: ClearParams
Methods.Comment: Remove all implicit querystring parameters.

Methods.Name: Client
Methods.Comment: Returns the HTTP client used to perform requests

Methods.Name: Decode
Methods.Comment: Decode a response and, if applicable, automatically close the reader.

Methods.Name: Delete
Methods.Signature: Delete(path string, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: Get
Methods.Signature: Get(path string, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: GetWithBody
Methods.Signature: GetWithBody(path string, body interface{}, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: Headers
Methods.Comment: Return the headers set on this client.

Methods.Name: Params
Methods.Comment: Return the params set on this client.

Methods.Name: Post
Methods.Signature: Post(path string, body interface{}, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: Put
Methods.Signature: Put(path string, body interface{}, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: Request
Methods.Comment: Perform an HTTP request
Methods.Signature: Request(method Method, path string, body interface{}, params map[string]interface{}, headers map[string]interface{}) (*http.Response, error)

Methods.Name: SetAutomaticLogin
Methods.Comment:
Specify that the NetrcFile (default: ~/.netrc) should be consulted before each
request to supply basic authentication.  If a non-empty username or password is
found for the

Methods.Name: SetBasicAuth
Methods.Comment: Set the username and password to be included in the Authorization header.

Methods.Name: SetClient
Methods.Comment: Replace the default HTTP client with a user-provided one

Methods.Name: SetDecoder
Methods.Comment: Specify a decoder that will be used to deserialize data in the response body.

Methods.Name: SetEncoder
Methods.Comment: Specify an encoder that will be used to serialize data in the request body.

Methods.Name: SetErrorDecoder
Methods.Comment: Specify a different decoder used to deserialize non 2xx/3xx HTTP responses.

Methods.Name: SetHeader
Methods.Comment:
Add an HTTP request header by name that will be included in every request. If
value is nil, the named header will be removed instead.

Methods.Name: SetInitHook
Methods.Comment:
Specify a function that will be called immediately before the first request is sent.
This function has an opportunity to read and modify the outgoing request, and
if it returns a non-nil error, the request will not be sent.

Methods.Name: SetInsecureTLS
Methods.Comment: Set or unset insecure TLS requests that will proceed even if the peer certificate cannot be verified.

Methods.Name: SetParam
Methods.Comment:
Add a querystring parameter by name that will be included in every request. If
value is nil, the parameter will be removed instead.

Methods.Name: SetPostRequestHook
Methods.Comment:
Specify a function tht will be called immediately after a response is received.
This function is given the first opportunity to inspect the response, and if it
returns a non-nil error, no additional processing (including the Error Decoder function)
will be performed.

Methods.Name: SetPreRequestHook
Methods.Comment:
Specify a function that will be called immediately before a request is sent.
This function has an opportunity to read and modify the outgoing request, and
if it returns a non-nil error, the request will not be sent.

Methods.Name: SetRootCA
Methods.Comment: Replace the existing RootCA bundle with an explicit set of trusted certificates.

Methods.Name: URI

Packages.Name: log
Packages.Synopsis:
Package log package provides convenient and flexible utilities for logging messages.

Overview

Logging is done by calling functions in this package that correspond to the
severity of the log message being output.  At the package level, a minimum
severity can be set.  Messages less severe than this minimum logging level will
not be output.

Color Expressions

In addition to the standard printf-style formatting options (as defined in the
standard fmt package), this package supports inline expressions that control the
output of ANSI terminal escape sequences.  These expressions allow for a simple
mechanism to colorize log output, as well as applying graphical effects like
bold, underline, and blinking text (for terminals that support it).

By default, color expressions will only be honored if os.Stdin is attached to a
pseudoterminal.  This is the case when the program is run on the command line
and is not piped or redirected to another file.  This default ensures that the
colors are visible only in a visual context, but do not corrupt files or
pipelines with ANSI escape sequences.  Color sequences can be explicitly enabled
or disabled by setting the EnableColorExpressions package variable.

Using color expressions in format strings is done by wrapping the expression in
${expr}.  The general format for color expressions is:

	foregroundColor[+attributes[:backgroundColor[+attributes]]]

Colors (foreground and background):
	black
	red
	green
	yellow
	blue
	magenta
	cyan
	white
	[0-255]: numeric 8-bit color (for 256 color terminals)
	reset: Reset all color and graphics attributes to their defaults

Foreground Attributes:
	b: bold text
	B: blinking text
	h: high-intensity (bright text)
	i: inverted/reverse colors
	s: strikethrough
	u: underline

Background Attributes:
	h: high-intensity (bright text)

Examples

Below are some examples showing various formatting options for logs.

	log.Info("Hello, world!")
	// [11:22:33 0001] INFO Hello, world!

	log.Warningf("The %q operation could not be completed.", "add")
	// [11:22:33 0002] WARN The "add" operation could not be completed.

	log.Errorf("There was an ${red}error${reset} opening file ${blue+b:white}%s${reset}", filename)
	// [11:22:33 0003] ERRO There was an error opening file /tmp/file.txt
	//                                   ^^^^^              ^^^^^^^^^^^^^
	//                                   red text           blue text on white background

Log Interception

It is sometimes useful to be able to act on logs as they are emitted, especially in cases where this
package is used in other projects that are imported.  Log Interceptors are called before each log
line is emitted.  The LogInterceptFunc is called with the level the message was emitted with, the
message itself as a string, and a stack trace struct that defines exactly where the log was emitted
from.

	// print a complete stack trace before every debug-level message that is encountered
	log.AddLogIntercept(func(level log.Level, line string, stack log.StackItems){
		if level == log.DEBUG {
			for _, item := range stack {
				fmt.Println(item.String())
			}
		}
	})

Writable Logger

The WritableLogger implements the io.Writer interface, acting as a bridge between byte streams from
various sources and the log package.  This is frequently useful in situations like parsing the
output of other programs.  A WritableLogger accepts a custom LogParseFunc that allows individual
lines being written to the WritableLogger to be parsed, rewritten, and given a log severity level.

	import (
		"os/exec"
		"github.com/ghetzel/go-stockutil/log"
	)

	wr := log.NewWritableLogger(log.INFO, `ls: `)

	wr.SetParserFunc(func(line string) (log.Level, string) {
		if strings.Contains(line, `root`) {
			// root-owned files show up as errors
			return log.ERROR, line
		} else if strings.Contains(line, os.Getenv(`USER`)) {
			// current user files are notices
			return log.NOTICE, line
		} else {
			// all other lines are not logged at all
			return log.DEBUG, ``
		}
	})

	ls := exec.Command(`ls`, `-l`)
	ls.Stdout = wr
	ls.Run()

an empty string, or a fallback value may be provided like so: "${path.to.value|fallback}".

"${path.to.value|fallback:%02d}" for fallback values.)  Finally, a special case for time.Time values
allows for the format string to be passed to time.Format: "${path.to.time:%January 2, 2006 (3:04pm)}".

ScanInterceptor.Name: ScanInterceptor

Methods.Name: BytesScanned
Methods.Comment: Return the total number of bytes this scanner has scanned.

Methods.Name: Intercept
Methods.Comment:
Add an intercept sequence and handler.  If the sequence is already registered, its handler
function will be replaced with this one.

Methods.Name: InterceptCounts
Methods.Comment: Returns a map of intercept sequences and the number of times each one was fired.

Methods.Name: Scan
Methods.Comment: Implements the bufio.SplitFunc function signature for use in a bufio.Scanner.
Methods.Signature: Scan(data []byte, atEOF bool) (advance int, token []byte, err error)

ScanInterceptor.Comment:
A ScanInterceptor is used as a SplitFunc on a bufio.Scanner.  It will look at the stream of bytes being scanned for
specific substrings.  The registered handler function associated with a substring will be called whenever it is seen
in the stream.  The passthrough SplitFunc is called as normal.  This allows for a stream to be
split and processed while also being inspected for specific content, allowing the user to react to that content
as it comes by.

Provides an API-compatible version of time.ParseDuration that accepts additional
formats for parsing durations:

  1w, 3weeks, 5wks:  Expands to (n*24*7) hours
  1d, 1day, 5days:   Expands to (n*24) hours

TimedReadCloser.Name: TimedReadCloser

Methods.Name: LastReadAt
Methods.Comment: Return the time of the last call to Read()

Methods.Comment:
Return a running duration of how long reading has been happening.  Updated on

Methods.Comment: Reset the internal counters to zero.  Useful after calling SetReadCloser().

Methods.Comment:
Set the underlying io.ReadCloser.  Does not call Reset(), so multiple ReadClosers
can be cumulitively tracked.

Methods.Comment: Return the duration of time since the last Read() occurred.

Methods.Comment: Return the time of the first call to Read().

TimedReadCloser.Comment:
A TimedReadCloser wraps an io.ReadCloser, keeping track of how long actually
reading from and closing the ReadCloser took, as well as how many bytes were read.

Measurement starts from the first call to Read(), and ends when Close() is called.
